{\pard \ql \sb0 \sa0 \sl0 \slmult1 \ilvl0 \li0 \lin0 \fi720 \ri0 \rin0 \s284 {\f1 \fs28 \lang1033 I have used two special symbols not usually found in Church romanization. Sandhi-juncture, explained below, is marked by a number-sign (#). In the H\'88\'6eb\'9e\'6e reading passages, the exclamation point (!) indicates that the preceding syllable is drawn out, which gives the tone the effect of dropping gradually in pitch. There is not necessarily a sandhi juncture at these places; sometimes the use of the prolongation is determined metrically. When applied to the }
{\f1 \fs28 \i \lang1033 y\'87\'6egp\'92\'6eg}
{\f1 \fs28 \i0 \lang1033  at a juncture boundary, the pitch of the syllable rises and then falls, not unlike the sound of the }
{\f1 \fs28 \i \lang1033 y\'87\'6egq\'9d}
{\f1 \fs28 \i0 \lang1033  syllable in Foochow dialect. At times Hung Tzeh-nan likes to give the }
{\f1 \fs28 \i \lang1033 y\'87\'6egp\'92\'6eg}
{\f1 \fs28 \i0 \lang1033  tone this rise-fall effect even without prolonging it.\par
}
}
{\pard \ql \sb360 \sa0 \sl0 \slmult1 \ilvl0 \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 \s282 {\f1 \fs28 \b \lang1033 . Stress and sandhi juncture\par
}
}
{\pard \ql \sb0 \sa0 \sl0 \slmult1 \ilvl0 \li0 \lin0 \fi720 \ri0 \rin0 \s284 {\f1 \fs28 \b0 \lang1033 Conventional descriptions of Taiwanese and M\bullet nn\'87\'6e dialects emphasize the principle of \ldblquote tone change\rdblquote , by which a \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  tone value is transformed into a \ldblquote changed\rdblquote  (or \ldblquote sandhi\rdblquote ) value in context. It has been observed, however, that speakers seem to treat the two values as structural allomorphs mediated by lexicon, and do not actually engage in a productive phonetic process (see the discussion in Myers and Tsai 2001:262-264). In keeping with this observation, it is preferable to use more plainly descriptive terms: the \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  contour of a tone category will be called its \ldblquote juncture\rdblquote  value (}
{\f1 \fs28 \i \lang1033 bi\'c1\'6eji\'8f\'64i\'88\'6f}
{\f1 \fs28 \i0 \lang1033  \f2 \'c3\'e4\'ac\'c9\'bd\'d5\f1 ) and the \ldblquote changed\rdblquote  contour its \ldblquote context\rdblquote  value (}
{\f1 \fs28 \i \lang1033 y\'bc\'6a\'93\'6egdi\'88\'6f}
{\f1 \fs28 \i0 \lang1033  \f2 \'bb\'79\'b9\'d2\'bd\'d5\f1 ). Juncture values are so called because their presence generally marks a syntactic boundary. In an ordinary sentence, whether spoken or literary, the majority of the syllables have context values, and only a few have juncture values. Juncture tone values are phonologically marked, and are indicated in transcription by a number-sign (#) following the tone-number. \par
}
}
{\pard \ql \sb360 \sa0 \sl0 \slmult1 \ilvl0 \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 \s282 {\f1 \fs28 \b \lang1033 . Final syllables in general}
{\f1 \fs28 \b0 \lang1033 \par
}
}
{\pard \ql \sb240 \sa0 \sl0 \slmult1 \ilvl0 \li0 \lin0 \fi720 \ri0 \rin0 \s283 {\f1 \fs28 \lang1033 With some exceptions, the last normally stressed syllable in a sentence exhibits its juncture tone value.\par
}
